w7TuOJweFraeH2HSUW_lWA.text: 2 stars. Because the food is outstanding I've been there twice and it's amazing every time. Even my non vegan friends and family love it. However both times I've gone the customer service from the employees have been terrible. The girls there are just one a terrible mood, too busy, and they're just plain rude. Please work on your customer service. I'd pick nami over this place 1,000 times. Nami is incredibly friendly and excited to serve you. So walk a couple steps over to nami for delicious food and great people. I'd rather starve than go to The Coronado and get treated like crap.

gVzA5-09XemGxw77QeA5Zw.text: REALLY impressed with this place. i'll set the scene...it's a weekend and one of our reg spots, Green/Nami, is only offering brunch and is SLAMMED. we were too hungry to wait and we didn't want breakfast - it was 1 p.m. son!...as we're driving away looking for lunch, the girl says Coronado looks good. we try it.  all of the servers were attentive and on-point. the food was amazely! we tried the red bean quesadilla which was one of the best quesadillas i've ever had. we tried the chili which was a nice amount of spicy but not too much...the front person was kind enough to let us know the chili sitch, that it may be HOT. i liked the iced tea selections. i liked the crowd...not TOO full but a healthy stream of customers.  i'd imagine if more of the Green/Nami crowd knew about this place, which is like 100 feet away, Coronado would be even more busy. Coronado has a really creative menu with a lot of interesting combos (such as a red bean quesadilla). we look fwd to going back.  //we tried  the cookies, which didn't suit our tastes...the mexican chocolate cookie was too spicy and not chocolate enough; the rosemary chocolate chip was too rosemary-heavy...we might try more of the baked goods, but it would be nicer if they covered the croissants and such, instead of leaving them out in the open. there are too many transactions around that front area to leave exposed food. that's about the only complaint. the open-air set-up would just prevent us from ordering uncovered items near the register.//  prices: not high, not low. right in the middle we thought.  plenty of parking but a dirt lot - not ideal if yer car is just-washed.  overall a really cool old house funky vegan place that delivers on service and flavor. we will return. i hope the experience is consistently this enjoyable.

XUUie3Iyk716kPWXOgKtWA.text: After just landing in Phoenix, my boyfriend and I (both vegetarians) found this little place on our way to the Grand Canyon. This place is tiny but oh so cute and cozy! We ordered at the counter and then found some seats outside. This is a great spot to hang out and relax for a nice meal, a good coffee, or even just a small bite.  We ordered the black coffee chili & cornbread and the potato tacos. The tacos were decent and we devoured them pretty fast, but the chili was so cold! The chili was literally near frozen in the center. We told someone immediately, and she apologized and brought us a new one right away. Unfortunately, this one was almost just as cold. The chili really was delicious though and we were pretty hungry, and so we decided not to say anything this second time and just "eat around the cold part."  To our surprise, a few moments later, the young woman that gave us the second chili presented us with a receipt refunding not just the chili but OUR ENTIRE ORDER! She also apologized to us again and thanked us for stopping by. During our visit, this place was just working out the kinks, since they were still quite new. The food itself was creative and delicious, and the customer service was impeccable!  We still ordered some coffees to go, because we just couldn't leave without spending a penny in such a friendly place!

-Un9w5iYW-G7OnX8RgWdmw.text: This place makes you wish you'd skipped an extra meal ahead of time so there would be more room in your stomach. SO GOOD! The potato tacos and fried guac are my two favorite things so far, but I'll have to try more of the menu before I can be sure ;)

isZ-Olfjz0Nnxp6Qw47rcg.text: My husband and I discovered this place and went here when we originally planned to go to another restaurant but they were closed on Sundays  I'm really glad we went here! We both had ordered the supposedly famous jackfruit sandwich, but they were out of jackfruit so the server gave us each a free pastry to make up for not being able to order what we had wanted.  We are both vegetarian, and have dabbled in being vegan, so the menu was right up our alley. Hubby ordered the potato tacos and I got the monte vista (sp?) sandwich, and we shared the street corn. The street corn was AMAZING, but they did give our order to another couple who had ordered the same thing but arrived after us, and so we ended up eating the corn after our main meal because it arrived so late. We also both got iced horchattes (horchatta lattes) which was a nice twist.  We sat outside since it was crowded inside, but there were misters and the patio is shaded so I didn't feel hot. They allow dogs on the outdoor patio which is good to know so we can bring our dog next time. :) Overall a good experience and I'm hoping to come back and try the jackfruit sandwiches sometime soon

Ao0uTJ0_jMhmCwR8i9HaWw.text: Food: I am not vegan or vegetarian (or even remotely close).I am a skeptic of any Mexican inspired food that claims to be both delicious and animal free since my compatriots love to eat even the ugliest part of an animal. Call me converted! The potato taco was DELICIOSO. I had no idea that potatoes could taste that way. Witchcraft! every single pastry I have eaten here has been perfect. they could sell this stuff in high end grocery stores and they SHOULD because this is America and our bellies demand it. Specifically - the sea salt Mexican wedding cookies & the dulce de leche filled cupcakes with meringue are delectable. I haven't eaten anything else here, so once I have I will come back and update. I usually give five stars for repeat performances.   Ambience: This restaurant is in a beautifully restored house in a historic neighborhood, so there are little nooks and crannies to explore both in and out of doors here. The decor is relaxed, clean and tasteful. Dog friendly porch included. There are theme nights with DJs and sweet music, so I am looking forward to attending one of those.  Note: I think it is important to keep expectations in order, here. The bar is small but mighty as is the staff. Good things come to those who wait, so remember you're not at McDonald's. The selections are proportional to the size of the whole operation, which is a bit on the smaller side. I say do a few things and do it well, so I am a fan of a small restaurant. Any foodie worth their salt knows that a 14-page menu is a bad sign. Though the menu is small, it is varied. It can get a bit crampy at the bar when you are ordering during high traffic times, so you might want to claim your stake at a table and take a menu with you to decide, then pop up to the bar to order when you're ready.  Edit: I am coming back to update to five stars. You can tell these owners really care about their community - locally and nationally. They team up with local vendors and have events to raise money for causes. 5 STARS!

Q7vi_NJue-WKykIlgbY0rQ.text: Good to have another vegetarian restaurant with many vegan options.   Creative menu and tasty HORCHATA!

KzX7J8iZZnR1_oGIrDe_wg.text: Ordered the goat cheese quesadilla with jalapeno marmalade and I literally could not eat it. The tortilla wasn't cooked, I quess they microwaved it to melt the goat cheese in it?   I love goat cheese but good GOD, it is rich and you don't need that much of it unless there is something added to cut the richness of it.  It came with a TINY splash of jalapeno marmalade. Not near enough!! I expected sweet (marmalade) and hot (jalapeno) and it wasn't spicy at all, only sweet.  NO Jalapeno flavor whatsoever maybe green bell pepper? Take it off the menu or do something to cut the richness of the cheese for GOD's sake.  It was awful!!   I go to the counter and tell the girl that it wasn't what I expected and that I wanted to order a salad.  I ordered the beet salad with goat cheese and she informed me that the salad had goat cheese on it.  I told her I knew that.  I informed her that I liked goat cheese just not how they prepared it in the quesadilla.  So she charged me for the salad and it came out with a TINY sprinkle of goat cheese.  Couldn't even taste it because there was so little of it.  Go figure!  Anyway, the salad was actually fantastic even with not enough goat cheese. It would have been even better had there been cheese on it.  I would recommend it if you like beets. I paid $22.00 for basically a salad since I couldn't eat the quesadilla so not exactly happy about it but better than having nothing to eat and paying $9.00 to starve.

a7XCAGzIU74io7D50iAJVw.text: The Coronado is one of the few places in town that does vegetarian/vegan food right.  They don't try to go overboard with holistic or intimidating ingredients. They don't try to make entrees that try too hard to substitute meat. They just take whole foods and turn them into ridiculously craveable plates.   The food is always delicious whether you're going for a weekend brunch, weekday happy hour, or late night meal. The cocktails are fresh and range from classic to experimental. The overall vibe is relaxed and grassroots.  So, don't fall for the assumption that vegetarian/vegan can't be satisfying; come to The Coronado and let them win you over with the palm and an order of potato tacos.

2wwG6wEezYMruFBKvy_wiQ.text: We arrived around 5:30 p.m. to beat the rush of Saturday diners. I am glad we did because we got a chance to look around the ecclectic house to find a table we liked. After claiming a spot as our own, I walked back up to the bar to place our order with the bartender. She was super nice and extremely knowledgeable about everything on the menu. We ordered fried guacamole, jackfruit sliders (we ordered it on sandwich bread, to make it vegan), and the burrito.    The chips that came with the guacamole were crisp and flavorful and the fries that accompanied the jackfruit sandwich and burrito were incredible. I don't usually eat fries, but these were the perfect size to enable the slightly crusted outside to contrast its soft, starchy inside. We cleaned our plates and we walked out full and happy.   We liked this place and will return again. It is awesome that their menu only contains vegetarian and vegan options. It shows that this place is definitely cognizant of compassion for animals and the environment.   Some other people's post talk about the menu being limited in choice. I actually prefer that because I tend to get the FOMO shakes. That is, the fear of missing out shakes. With a limited menu, it makes making a confident decision so much easier.

vC43YqLtcn6IukpB-jWd6Q.text: I am sitting on the front porch of The Coronado as I write this review. This is my second visit. The trees and rafters are still dripping from a fresh rain. (It rained last time I was here, too.)  I like this place - the charm of it. There is plenty of seating, both inside and out, and the interior features some really cool artwork, too. The bar is small but clean, and well-stocked for the size.  The first time I visited, my friend and I ordered food: the chili/cornbread and the potato tacos. Both dishes were very dry. We were not impressed, but we enjoyed our time here anyway.  There was also a small mishap with the coffee filters last time... I ordered a pour-over and, after nearly 30 minutes of waiting, was told that the filters kept breaking so I wouldn't be getting any hot coffee that night. Very strange. I had them bring me a tea instead.  This time, I have ordered the root beer they have on tap (a GENIUS addition to the menu, in my humble opinion). It is very tasty. I would order it again for sure.  Despite the subpar dishes (to my taste) and the unusual case of defective filters, I can't help but like this place. It has all the elements one might expect of a small neighborhood cafe.  The staff has always been super friendly, too, which counts for a lot in my book. The Coronado is a new addition to the area - I think it will do well. If you've never been, stop by for a root beer! If you want it to rain, just sit on the front porch - it's worked for me every time!  ;)

Aoil3t7UBQPCPvWJnp-j0Q.text: I must start by saying that I love the food at the coronado!!! However, the service is lacking. The time it takes to receive you food is atrocious. I literally came in and ordered a biscuit,jam, and eggs. 15 minutes later no food.  The excuse is there was a to go order for an order of 30 tacos. Well 15 minutes prior I was the one ordering the to go. Why did the other order take priority over mine? It is always something with the wait time aside from today. Although the food is amazing, my time is precious and don't have time to wait 20 - 30 plus minutes for something as simple as a side item biscuit and jam. Once they get more help, a bigger kitchen or better location to accommodate the thriving business I'll come back.

YpiLnt-isPatCHDej19Kaw.text: This place is terrible. The food we received was overcooked and incredibly bland. When we complained to the manager/owner they acted as if we were lucky to even have the opportunity to dine at their restaurant. The food is awful and so is management. Avoid this place.

zwjeMvFl58SfSeretGFfIA.text: I want to love this place and my first visit I did. I'm actually really sad to give this place 2 stars, because on a good day they are 5 stars, but that's the problem. Consistent quality.   My first visit, I had just an app and a cocktail, and I was blown away. It was so good! My next visit, tried those famous cauliflower tacos and was blown away- so good.  The visit I tried potato tacos. They were not great. Really dry and bland. I thought, maybe this just isn't the right thing to order. I tasted my friends chorizo and tofu tacos and they were pretty good though.  Next visit, apparently the manager went on vacation and didn't order any food. They were out of 60% of the menu. We got the fried guacomole- just unfried because they didn't have any of the crumbs. Went ahead and ordered the cauliflower tacos and the chorizo tacos, since they were out of nearly everything else. This time the cauliflower was fried too long and dark brown and soggy. Still edible, but not as delicious.  Then take another friend yesterday. We split cauliflower tacos and jackfruit sandwhich. 2 of the 3 cauliflower tacos are awesome. The 3rd has raw coating on half of the cauliflower... wet sticky brown stuff. That was not good. Then the jackfruit sandwhich. Sorry for this... Yuck. It was gross. I cook jackfruit too. To be more detailed than "yuck". It was bland, like no salt or seasoning. There wasn't any pop to the flavor, no salt, no acid. The texture was mainly mushy with a mild sweet undertone. It was just disgusting. I tried adding lots of salt and lime juice... anything I could put on it to make it palatable. It was just terrible. The salad that came with was good.  So, this place is hit or miss. It bums me out, because I am strictly plant based and really appreciate vegan restaurants that do more than just fake meats. The staff is always polite, the casual atmosphere is cool, but if the food is great one day disgusting the next. Well, that's not okay- that doesn't qualify for 3-4 or 5 stars. They have to get it together. I really hope they do too, because it could should and has been great.

TOZJa74gncl0dra2I0AUrw.text: This is the best restaurant I have been to in a long time. It is very cute with a very comfortable atmosphere. They also have a dog friendly patio. The only thing that would make it better is more seating. We had the fried guacamole, cauliflower tacos and chili guacamole fries. Everything was fantastic. Even my meat eating husband was raving about the food. We got some desserts before we left; a hibiscus cookie sandwich, a walnut brownie and a salted peanut butter blondie. The blondie was WAY too salty and pretty dry, the brownie was good, but the cookie was incredible! We ended up buying two more. Even if you aren't vegan or vegetarian, The Coronado won't leave you disappointed. I can't wait to go back!

sxhiIBsJFkIYLwoUsDFz9A.text: I was kinda dismayed by the counter service at first but everyone was super helpful and guided me though my first time in. I would definitely go back. I went in expecting weird hippy vegetarian food and found really good hippy vegetarian food! So if you got someone who is afraid of this kind of food like I am, bring them here and I can't see how they won't enjoy this place.

z2t6U1YmxXSsgz-a7sN-Tw.text: Unfortunately I can't eat here anymore. I have tried this place 10-15 times since they have been open and I just can't. Even though the food quality is good the combinations are no better than the "green" vegetarian place across the street. A for the effort but a C- for the food. Here is the dilemma. Small place ok, short and to the point menu ok, but it's not well balanced nutritiously. You not eating processed soy crap but too much embellishments of non nutrient packed foods and breads, and other things. I get it and I want to support small businesses but I want well thought out quality NUTRIENT packed foods that tastes good! Trust me it possible just look at True Foods. Another thing I have noticed is the prices have went up like $2-$3 for each item...ok makes sense again but I am going to see more veggies, better ingredient like 0 canola oil you know stuff like that happen to feel like it worth it.Nevertheless give this place a try if you don't mind skipping on the nutrient here and there.... otherwise you may feel blah leaving the place.

a7jNXynTqW5-kil-Glnw5Q.text: This place is absolutely wonderful and charming. My friend brought me here promising I would love it, and I was not disappointed. The menu is filled with delicious-sounding items and coffee - including a Horchatte that I really wanted to try but knew would upset my stomach (I have a hard time with sugary foods).  I ordered the goat cheese and jalapeno marmalade quesadilla and a mixed drink I can't remember the name of (it was whiskey and wine?! omg). The atmosphere here is absolutely perfect with each room feeling cozy. It's well decorated, and the staff is friendly. I couldn't stop staring at everything on the walls! Even the bathroom had awesome art. My friend had the Good Morning Sandwich, and even though they were out of both suggested bread replacements, they offered another option quickly and apologetically. Apparently their sourdough is popular!   My quesadilla was easily one of the best things I've eaten in a long time. It had just the right amount of goat cheese that perfectly paired with the jalapeno. I've been missing good spicy Mexican-inspired food, and this hit the spot. I ordered something spicy, and it was ACTUALLY spicy. I don't get that in my hometown of Pittsburgh too often! Each bite was heaven for me; I would eat this again and again if I had to. Not only was the food freaking delicious, it was also beautiful. For such simple items, they put effort into the appearance as well, which I fully appreciated.   Other menu items seemed super exciting too. I rarely go somewhere and want to try all the things because I am so picky, but their menu is perfect from top to bottom. It's pretty rare that I am this pleased with food, but Phoenix is treating my appetite quite well! I highly recommend The Coronado.   Bonus: Their hours are pretty long, 6am-10pm.

G-WliiTBydn9csdW57n55Q.text: My Wife and I came here last week for a late lunch.  You see, Junior was out of town on a school trip and my wife took the week off, so we had a "staycation" and were able to enjoy some restaurants we don't normally get to, The Coronado being one of them.   9 months ago, we decided to try a Vegan diet. I'll spare the details, but it's been a great choice for us.  My Brother and Sis'-in-law got us a gift card for this establishment for Christmas, and we finally made it down to try it.   For those that have not been there, The Coronado is located in a small renovated house on the N/E corner of 7th Street an Monte Vista.  Being that we went at an off time, we had no problem parking in the dirt lot on the north side of the restaurant.  I'd describe the interior as eclectic and hipster modern.  When you enter the front door, the counter/drink area is off to your left.  We were greeted by the young lady behind the counter and told that we order at the counter, and our food will be brought out to our table.    My Wife and I grabbed a table in the back room and checked out the menu.  We kept going back and forth between tacos and burgers; we decided on the latter.  We went up front to the counter and ordered our meals, the Tepary Bean Burger with fries for my wife, and the Red Potato Garbanzo Burger with salad and a side of fries (we are on staycation after all...) for me and 2 iced teas to drink.  We also selected the focaccia bread as the vegan option over the buttermilk bun.  The young lady at the counter brought us our teas (they are made fresh when you order) after a few minutes.  Another server brought out our food a couple of minutes after the teas.  Both the burgers looked hidden under the focaccia bread, but the salad and the homemade fries (long thick cut) looked great; it was at this point that I noticed my burger was slathered with mayonnaise.  I purposely selected the Red Potato and Garbanzo burger because of the 3 burgers listed on the menu, it's the only one without mayo, yet here I am looking at a thick spread of mayo (vegan or otherwise, I don't like mayo) peaking out at me from under the focaccia.    Well...as I've stated before, I don't send food back, ever; and even if I wanted to, the server was nowhere to be found.  She had dropped off our food and disappeared at almost light speed.  So...I made do with what I had and tried to enjoy my burger.  Both burgers were tasty, but crumbly which is understandable considering what they are made from.  My wife liked hers, and from what I could taste of mine, it was quite good; unfortunately the mayo not only hid the flavor of the burger, but also the agave mustard which was disappointing.  I also don't think that focaccia bread is a great choice for a vegan burger, since it's more dense and harder than the burger it's supporting; try getting some soft vegan rolls, other restaurants do it.  As I mentioned above, the french fries were home made and thick cut.  They looked wonderful and were seasoned nicely.  However, they were not cooked long enough.  They were flaccid.  A little more time in the fryer, and they would have been much better.  The catsup served on the side did have a very nice flavor.  The side salad I had with my burger was the high point of my meal, the dressing was light and very tasty.  The mixed greens were fresh and so were the tomatoes.  When we had finished our meals, yet another person showed up to take our plates.  No one checked on us while we were eating to see if we needed anything, no refills of our drinks were offered.  We left; full, but unsatisfied.    Before our visit, we had no idea of the controversy involving the owner of this restaurant, we simply had a gift card and wanted to try a new stop on our vegan journey.  My advice to the owner...spend more time in your restaurant overseeing your staff and making sure they can properly prepare, cook, and serve the food on your menu and less time trying to drive away half the population from your establishment.

BhDVJBmC3BzFC-QPJUD01g.text: Was in Phoenix for the weekend and stumbled upon this place. It was SO amazing, an absolute vegan dream. The cashew pesto and gravy are absolutely fantastic! Great coffee too, brunch here was great and if ur in the area vegan or not, this is the place!

7fIcm4rBPf2PUGn41rfs0Q.text: RUDE STAFF!!!  I was a frequent visitor to the coronado and would always make the 20 min drive. But after yesterday I will definitely not visit and I will stop telling all the people I know to visit. We were at the establishment for over 30 mins waiting for our food and then a food runner finally sees us and says your ticket number got confused I think your food has been sitting there I will get it. He then brings out our now room temperature food and then realizes that they never even made the kids cheese crisp. My niece was super hungry and fussy so I went to talk to a manager and as the manager is checking on it I kind of started venting to a worker that I see ALL the time and am always kind to. I tell her I'm sorry I realize it wasn't you who took the order but that I know my brother is always a good tipper it's just a little frustrating we come here all the time(we just spent over 80 dollars here) and her response in a rude tone is "yea you should tip 20% and you come here all the time so you should know we are busy and are all human and make mistakes" I was like woah then my brothers girlfriend came to let me know to forget about it because she could hear how she was talking to me. Then when I went to let my brother know what she said she left her spot from behind the bar to run up to our table and scold me some more in her loud rude tone that there is nothing more they can do and that they are checking on it. It was a super weird and embarrassing situation, I was always taught that the customer is always right, I wasn't screaming I was frustrated and venting to an employee that I saw all the time and maybe could understand that there was a fussy hungry 3 year old and I just got off of a plane and we drove straight there to enjoy their food, offer a cookie that they sell for 4 dollars, ask if I need a drink refill(which my prickly pear Arnold Palmer was mainly all watered down lemonade). Don't tell the customer to get over it. Not the kind of customer service I want in a business especially the amount of money and the miles it takes to get there. This was not the first time I have experienced attitude here this just takes the cake. I see a lot of reviews talking about it, maybe it's the same person and it's time to clean up shop or have a work shop class on how to treat customers. I know I would be sent home immediately if I thought I could talk to a customer like that.

iJyPgUe8R69ARYmplvthuA.text: Went on a recommendation from a friend. I enjoyed the food enough to forget that I was eating vegan/vegetarian. We had breakfast on Saturday and the place was busy but not full. Parking is limited. There was plenty of outside seating (dog friendly if that is important for you). We enjoyed their baked cookies and pastries as well as the chili fries and biscuits with gravy. The "kitchen sink (?)" cookie was interesting. Seemed to be whatever they had left over, sunflower seeds plus others, and honestly, even without knowing, I still was jealous the kids ate most of it. I would go again if I'm in the area, no question. Great people, service and food.

szW3PMjzX0il9xtCsA5S_Q.text: Awesome chia seed pudding and vegan friendly biscuits and gravy! Unfortunately it's a little small so it fills up quick forget going on the weekend around brunch! Good drink selection as well with a cozy environment. Nice outside seating if the weather permits.

jQpsDvJETZuMoczA8JBcmA.text: Excellent vegan food, friendly servers, and owners who CARE about not only their community (and do weekly fundraisers for various orgs to prove it) but also pay a living wage AND provide health & dental insurance to all of their employees. Show me another locally-owned restaurant that can say the same.   I have frequented this place since it opened, coming here with friends for bike-in music nights, on first dates, and for Sunday breakfast with my kids.   Try the fried guac, potato tacos, beet burger with fries, jalapeno-marmalade & goat cheese quesadilla; and so many more delicious items to choose from! Cocktails are creative and tasty; beer and wine also available, as well as delicious vegan pastries and a full range of espresso beverages.   Housed in a renovated old home in the heart of central Phoenix, with a nice shaded patio (misters on in summer) this is a place not to miss!

a4yAQ1v0_ui_AGORYli_Qw.text: Everything was delicious. I tried the burrito, avocado toast, chimichanga, and the chili with corn bread. My favorite was the chili with corn bread and the burrito was pretty amazing too. They had really good flavors. The sauce that came with the burrito was amazing. I tried the vegan horchata but I wouldn't recommend it. It tastes a little watered down. But overall the food and service was great. I highly recommend the chili and burrito!

uWSdfDBFzNuP39K7X6Osyw.text: Absolutely phenomenal vegan and vegetarian options. Every dish ordered at my table was superb.  A must-visit if you're looking for a great vegan dining experience w/ a cool ambience.

UCcIHAylrpuxlrQ5hlExIg.text: I went here today with some friends and their sweet small dog. The bar manager smiled at us when we walked in and complimented our dog. My friends and I proceeded to order food and drinks. Having spent the money (a lot of it) we waited inside for our food. A waitress with short brown hair came up to us and told us the dog was not allowed in the restaurant. We did not know this considering there were other dogs at the restaurant and the fact that the bar manager told us our dog was cute. I proceeded to ask if there was any seating outside and the waitress said no. To add, the outdoor seating was FULL. I asked if we were able to get seats outside and a table to sit at considering we just spent a good amount of money at this restaurant (to sit and eat at). We would have happily ate outside, but I would assume a restaurant would provide enough seating for paying customers. Beware, SMALL patio. The waitress refused to get us a table. She was extremely rude and made offensive comments to us. I have never had such a bad restaurant experience in my life, and I eat out daily. This waitress should be fired the way she handled the situation. I am completely shocked at the nasty unhappy attitude these staff have. No staff in the restaurant seemed to know what do to. Staff scrambling around like chickens with their head cut off. Never again will I ever spend my money or time at a negative place like this that treats their customers with no respect. NONE. This is my only time posting a review and I believe this needs to be shared.

N8zQXnoA4QjBy5KG8RGyWw.text: I hadn't been back to The Coronado since the menu change, so I decided to drop in for a couple of things. The quaint cafe-esque atmosphere was the same and I had a reason to knock out a rosemary chocolate chip cookie. (It was staring me down, so I showed it who was boss.)  I ordered:  - $9.00 Cauliflower Tacos which are masa-battered cauliflower florets on top of guacamole, chopped spinach, pepitas, and avocado dressing  - $11.00 Red Potato and Garbanzo Burger which is a potato and garbanzo bean patty accompanied with spinach and tomato/agave mustard on a buttermilk bun.  Well...let me start by saying TC does have interesting combinations, but the food is overkill. Can't fault them there, though, because no where does the restaurant claim to serve healthy food.   My plates were tasty and comforting, but thinking of the quantities of oil consumed, it was less healthier than I prefer when eating out. I actually went home and ate a huge salad after that.  Here are my thoughts on how the dishes could be better:  I don't know why anyone would order the potato garbanzo burger with a side a fries. The patty by itself was delicious, soft, and falls apart easily. Unfortunately taste was overpowered by the thick starch-overloaded bun. The side salad I opted for was a pretty green arugula salad. It meant well, but the quantity was so small I could have easily used it as garnishment for the sandwich. Need more salad!  One thing annoyed me about the sandwich. The menu made no mention of mayo, but the cook spread mayo (vegan I presume - YUCK!) on the bun. So not only was the sandwich more oily on my tongue, it was slippery to bite into too. I wanted to slap the cook -- not for a good reason.  For anyone that doesn't like thick buns, I suggest asking if they would substitute a wrap or pita pocket. Even a lettuce wrap would be much better than that thick buttermilk thing.    As for the cauliflower tacos, once again the delivery was over done. Masa breading AND corn tortilla? Come on. The fried masa is oily and once it's cold it falls off into the guacamole (naturally oil rich). The tacos would taste much better with roasted cauliflower.   But anyway, I'm not a cook. I just eat. Three stars for the food this time around.

dIUaOt9yNwJ6ooLYz8RPZw.text: Delicious cauliflower tacos!!! Must get if you're here. The southwest salad is really good too. They also have began baked goods , fresh juice and assorted coffee I got cold brew and horchlatte which I really liked !

i0MRGu039OwpU7M73K6-AA.text: Found this place on my iPhone "maps" while looking for vegetarian restaurants (I'm a vegetarian, obv).  What a lucky find on my part.  If I lived a little bit closer (20 minute drive) I'd be there almost every day.  The whole menu is vegan, but my non-vegan friends and sons can't even tell judging by taste.  Every item I've tried on the menu has been great.  The setting in an old house is so cool and unique.  The location, the vibe, the food, the crowd, it's all great.  Selfishly I hope it doesn't get too big because I love the feeling of knowing a great little spot that most mainstream ppl don't know about, but I wish them all the success they can possibly achieve.  Staff is full of hustlers that seem passionate about the place succeeding.  A++

YnLfhFnpJXjzvrQJDUlSqw.text: I can't believe I haven't reviewed The Coronado yet! I have been at least 5 times, and each time has been very good! The Coronado is a vegetarian restaurant from the people behind Bragg's Factory Diner (which I loved and was so upset when it closed). I was so happy to see the Bragg's people opened a new place.... and improved it with a full bar! The Coronado is a great place for coffee, drinks, breakfast, dessert and happy hour. They have a delicious cocktail that involves horchata...not sure what it's called, but it's fabulous. You can get this drink on the cheap until 7 pm.... I repeat, 7 pm!!! Hooray for late happy hours.   As good as their hh is, I think their breakfast is even better. They have an amazing egg sandwich served on a delicious flaky biscuit, topped with perfectly cooked veggies and a fabulously sweet/savory mustard sauce. I (almost) didn't miss the meat.   While your there, you have to get at least one baked good. I have had some amazingly delicious cookies and cupcakes here... the selection is always different and consistently impressive.   I highly recommend The Coronado to vegetarians and meat eaters alike!  PS 1500!!!

mIAaqerXi_xWeKZhKOO2cw.text: I just moved from Seattle and am trying to find new places to go. Which to be honest doesn't happen often. I'm pretty happy just meandering neighborhoods walking my dog. I will have to remedy that. This place reminds me of my coffee shop back home. It's a community hub, it's great coffee, the menu looks enticing to this carnivore, and apparently when friends come into town to play a show they end up here! Bummed I missed that event, I hope Sammy and Curtis comes back there again.  So I think I've found my favorite coffee shop officially. Bonus is that there is a dog friendly patio!

dADaQ_XQrDLzPHNheGt6MQ.text: I found this place a few yrs ago and loved it.  It was close to airport and opened late.  However past few visits were the worst. Service was so bad as i am now sure they r racist. Look at my other posts i have never stated a business was racist.  The service is bad and food the give me is crap.  For example i ordered the biscuits and gravy. IT WAS COLD. The biscuits were so dry and they provided a little gravy.  I asked for more gravy hoping it will come hot. But the girl said she will charge.  Ok but does she see the little bit i was given for dry biscuits. Fuck it.  I will remove them for my places to eat

97MsB1htZKXoFT1dy4-DKw.text: On both of my recent visits to The Coronado, expectations have been exceeded! On my first visit, I went with the guacamole fries ... Hand-cut fries topped with fresh guac and vegan chili.  That's pretty much a vegan's heaven for indulgence foods. I could not finish this order.  Ate about half of it and saved the rest for another meal.  I also had a small salad on the side which was perfect to lighten up my meal of fries!   The second visit I had the cauliflower tacos... I didn't think they could top the chili-guac fries, but they did!  I will definitely be back for those tacos!  I also got a s'mores cookie sandwich.  This was two choc chip cookies sandwiched with a fluffy vanilla-ish frosting type of substance.  It was good, DECADENT, but not like a s'mores.  I'm sort of a s'mores-aholic, so I'm a tough critic.  I should also note it was very oily.  Soaked through the paper baggie they put it in for to-go orders.  I'd suggest less butter substitute and darker chocolate in the cookie recipe, and something containing marshmallows on the inside filling.    Its a small place, but they've always had table open when I've stopped in towards the end of happy hour.  It is counter service, so place your order at the front, take your number and sit and wait for the deliciousness.

5jRrddLTMuWZU943sOf9ag.text: The two stars is because their food is good. It's just hoping they get your order right is the struggle. Have had 3 postmates orders with the Coronado and all 3 were wrong. and when I called to let me know they simply said "OK" No sorry no we will do better. just "OK" Every item that had a quantity of more than one on our order they only sent one Not cool. We have people now in our office with no food even though they paid. Also might want to go over with the cook how to cook eggs ordered over medium got hard fried

GTvIUf1eW0-pPqLQrBh1BA.text: My gf and I love The Coronado. The chill atmosphere, prompt service, and fresh food keep us coming back quite often.   They really should know us by name here, haha.   Her favorites are the vegan pancakes which they only offer on the weekends from 10am-2pm I believe. Never had better vegan pancakes.   We are both pretty fond of the potato tacos.   My personal favorite is the beet burger. I get it almost every time I go and it never fails me.   Also, this may sound basic but their fries too omg! Always on point and fresh!  It's counter service then everything else is self serv (napkins, forks, water, etc) so at times we've felt kind of like a burden asking for things. I'm not a fan of that aspect BUT it's really a laid back atmosphere and the staff is nice.   For sweets we go for the brownies and the muffins. Blueberry is my fave! Whoever bakes those things have very special hands.   They have fresh squeezed orange juice too (need I say more about that?) haha  Outside seating available(doggy friendly :)).  Bathroom photos scare me though. Can't go into the bathrooms alone bec I'm a wimp obvi.   Oh! And they just added stuff to the menu. I tried the fried chimichanga and YUM!   4 stars because the customer service can definitely be strengthened. I'm not wowed by it but my overall experience every time I go is worth returning for!

tZwklNar8TrhigNDZKib0w.text: Without a doubt, the best meal of my recent trip through New Mexico, Arizona and southern California was at The Coronado in Phoenix. And -- much to my surprise and delight -- it was totally vegetarian/vegan!  This is not a fancy restaurant -- though it is somewhat quaint and quirky (check out the photos on the restroom walls). You order and pay at the counter, you get a number, you get your drinks at the bar, you select a table somewhere in the bungalow or on the patio, and you wait for your food to come.   I ordered a "bean burger" (a tepary bean and mushroom patty topped with roasted tomatoes, arugula & vegan mayo on a bun) along with fries and a beer. The flavor, the texture, the condiments, the bun, and the overall quality of the "burger" was excellent. Even meat eaters (such as I normally am) will be fully sated. And the fries were as good as any I have eaten at any establishment. Should a carnivore end up eating here with vegan friends (or by accident) the fries alone should satisfy them. A side of grilled street corn on the cob swimming in vegan mayo and dusted with spices was also quite good.   My only complaint -- and it is a small one -- is serving beer in pint jars. Yes, it assures me that I received a pint, but I like real beer glasses.  So -- herbivores, carnivores, and omnivores alike -- If you like tasty food you should be satisfied at The Coronado PHX.

MirxNroxJHuj4AX8MpwPDA.text: Come here if:  - You would like to wait 30 minutes without any update for your food (simple burrito and an avocado toast) -OR if you want the restaurant to completely not make your order because they trashed your order ticket as"they thought it was a duplicate" like the lovely, unfortunate couple ahead of us.  Food is average.  Pass on this one.  A not so bright endcap for our trip to Phoenix.

W5m9P1EwnN_5DVTwSF4lTw.text: 25+ minute wait for two dishes. A very sad single avocado toast that could have been made in 5 minutes max. Breakfast burrito...was a far measure from the classic breakfast burrito I've ever seen. After the food arrived I was fixated the entire time on how it took this long to make rabbit-sized food. Beware of the other positive reviews here. At least 10 other parties ordered around the same time as us and no one else had their food when we left. Shame.

Jwd64CYJne5l-Qy4r2j0fg.text: I come here quite often, I like to get the pastries, alcoholic drinks, and the food of course. My favorite dishes would be the red bean quesadilla, the fried guac and chips, and the cauliflower tacos. All very delicious.  Oh and you must try the homemade pop tarts! Flaky and delectable! I love how this place is set up. It's like a little home, feels comfortable and cozy. The staff are always really nice with great attitudes to help with anything you may need. Thank you everyone! Can't wait to come back.

djs5DJrUSZDz2dlbW2Bljg.text: Great spot for vegan/vegetarian dining and one of my favorite brunch places in Phoenix. Especially enjoy their biscuits and gravy for breakfast. Also have decent beer list and cocktails available.

29kHzFgga-8iT8zmvdOTjw.text: I really want this to be our go to place for family breakfasts on the weekend because I have so many fond memories of weekend meals out with my family growing up and I want the same for my kids. And even though I go with my kids and I always see people there with kids, this is just not a family friendly restaurant. I can't quite figure out why. Maybe it's because when I ask for a side of fruit they look at me like I have 3 heads. How hard can it be to put some cut fruit in a bowl and upcharge by a magnitude of 10? Seems like an easy win. Maybe it's because of the contemptuous glares from the cashier person on repeat as my kids are joyfully playing games at our table. Sure they're loud, but they're not screaming in anger, we're talking sounds of children's laughter here. I would understand if this was Friday night fine dining, but it's Sunday morning, the doors are open and I can hear the city bus offloading outside. Maybe it's because they can't seem to serve plain pancakes before 10am. It doesn't seem like it would be that hard to do but they've assured me it is. I've asked. But honestly, it's probably because they don't want to be family friendly. Or benefit of the doubt, maybe they don't know they're not family friendly because not enough of the staff has kids. It's one of the two. Don't get me wrong, I get that it's not their job to cater to me and my 2 year old twins. I'm just putting this out there in case anyone else shared my longing for a family friendly vegan spot. I'll still be looking and going to Scramble for now where I can get vegan french toast and be home before 10am. And I'll probably still come to Coronado every few months hoping for that fruit cup and early morning pancakes because I'm a glutton for punishment.   Shout out for the always delish food and the nice guy who offered me a bag when he saw me trying to manage the diaper bag, a toddler and 2 take out boxes.

OiJ44MPGU7ll_vmvswcV6Q.text: Some vegan friends turned me on to this downtown gem. Started out with the tacos & Mexican street corn, which were both phenomenal!!! XbliD-uFCYfbuJFQFW1Vzw.text: We stopped by for brunch on Saturday morning. The restaurant Feels like a house that was converted into a restaurant. You order at the front and then sit down and food is brought your table. The restaurant has a tremendous variety of options for vegetarians and vegans. hnL7t9ftMh24F53vfieenw.text: Favorite vegan spot in Phoenix! It's very down to earth feel and the food is amazing. I haven't had a dish here that I didn't love. Dog friendly patio with water bowls as well :)

Zme0BjFRrlUFiqgqYy9dzw.text: I didn't know what to expect when we walked in. We were headed home after a business appointment downtown and we were suddenly famished. There were lots of interesting looking restaurants but my husband had heard of this place so decided to dine here.   We parked on the side street because near noon the parking lot was already full. We walked in through the patio and entered the old house which is now the restaurant. It was cozy and lively music was playing. We grabbed a menu and stood in a short line. I was in the mood for a big juicy burger. That was not to be the outcome. This place is vegetarian and vegan. The burgers didn't look appealing to me but the menu was very interesting. We both decided on the huevos rancheros and what a score! They were delicious. We were served two corn tortillas topped with a veggie chili, light cheese and two perfectly cooked eggs. I was full by the time we were finished. I really wanted to try something from the pastry case but I am still eating light after a glutinous Thanksgiving. Darn it!    Service was friendly and food came out on a reasonable time in spite of the noon hour. I'd go back and be more adventurous next time and I'll grab a scone there too!

u7oL_yK3vJJ4zUZBMuYFLw.text: Best coffee I've had in the US (I'm an nyc resident).  The cauliflower tacos were yummy and the breakfasts were delicious and healthier than I expected.  Phoenix surprises with its abundance of vegan/veg options.  The service and staff were muy excelente!!  Gracias!!

tz_HjFa3oe0w3TORXrwGhA.text: Great for vegetarians. Best of all, the food is delicious and thoughtfully presented. The staff is also doing very well. Parking can be a problem during lunch, but otherwise adequate.

i3SXLnhZxDS5aPhgsjzDFw.text: So so. It's more of a hangout than a restaurant. I'll probably never go back. There are much better new eateries in the surrounding area.

RdKjagLU6R-JYm3nLCfOgQ.text: Finally a vegan establishment that understands the necessity of flavoring their foods !!!!! I've never finished my entire plate from vegan places other than here. Everything I've had has been wonderful flavor same with desserts I can't wait to keep trying more !!

wU9EGqHhbp78xtV9SWzoiQ.text: I have never been to a vegan/vegetarian restaurant as good as this. Fucking fantastic! I just moved down from Utah and they don't have shit there, now I am eating my heart out at all these wonderful places. g-IDGA0ljs4-tFzxfZ-0vw.text: The food is awesome! We had the cauliflower tacos and jalapeno marmalade and goat cheese quesadillas. The service is quick and friendly. z_HSUffNhDBijjIx1G4n5w.text: Yesterday's brunch got me like  .. e_2Zx9S7BNEQxgTwQI4JBA.text: Right across from Green and Nami, The Coronado is a house converted into a restaurant. Upon entering, they had coffee, beer, and pastries. I ordered from the happy hour menu, which is a huge chunk of the menu, and got my number. I chose patio seating on these huge patio tables. I picked the fried guacamole, which was pretty standard, and the red bean quesadilla. I didn't think this would be good, but it was amazing! It's savory with red peppers and a nacho cheeze sauce on top and they provide huge portions. I only ate half and saved the rest for later - unfortunately, the tortilla got soggy so it wasn't as good the next day.

6l8haHSpzMSwwqwvppPfqA.text: Solid place. I got the red potato and chick pear burger, and my boyfriend got the beet and quinoa burger. They were both really good, however I think adding something like grilled mushrooms or onions and maybe even avocado would make it a lot better! It just needed more. It was also a smaller sized portion.   Ranch would also be good with the fries :)

s2oZll9FJZQQ7_5yrVlP-Q.text: Love a place that puts its money where it's morals are.  Thanks for being the love!!!

eAM-KtflXi-xHDaqJg1uCA.text: I loved the ambiance .  The staff was friendly and paid attention to food preferences. The food was fresh and full of flavor.  It was satisfying and filling. Horchata was delicious.  It was a beautiful day and enjoyed eating al fresco

08NhI29mSzWIqe3wrR7eAA.text: Quirky little place with great staff and vegetarian food. Indoor and outdoor seating options. Neighborhood feel. Looks like lots of locals and friends eat here. Coffee was spot on. Some parking out back but if full there is street parking. We would eat here again if in the area.

itvGupYpUUGZHNQj1tQrOA.text: I'm thrilled to say that this is one of my favorite places. Outdoor seating that's dog-friendly and intimate indoor seating, the Coronado is intimate while still feeling relaxed. It's got a pastry case, has great beer and the cauliflower tacos are one of the best things I've ever eaten.

ix4K_SCfzy5Y0Yr8sfFq0A.text: Would of taken a photo of my food, but I ended up eating it all before I even thought to write this. I ordered the red bean quesadilla...BOMB!!  Stop reading this and stop by this place asap!

EIXWYDdle1Xg88JoAIU8BQ.text: Good flavors and choices.  It was self-serve...order at the bar and the food was delivered to the table.  After you order, pick up your napkins and silverware on your way back to the table.  We really enjoyed the tacos!

v--X0FQTwV20DPS1GSTTyw.text: I've been eating here since they opened and I'm consistently impressed with the friendliness of the employees, the delicious food, and the consistent willingness for the company to stand up for the rights of those the current administration is attempting to silence. Come into the Coronado at any time and you'll find some sort of cash collection jar for local LGBTQ+ rights groups or even for raising protest money for fighting the Dakota pipeline. Every employee has been nothing but kind, even during their busiest times.   Recently, I've been calling in my orders to go on my way home from class and they've still provided the same great, quick service. Some of my favorites include the cauliflower tacos, biscuits and gravy, fried guacamole, and breakfast sandwich with tofu. Drink wise, you can't go wrong with a nice chai, and they're always happy to make it according to taste, whether you prefer a more spicy chai or sweet. They've recently expanded the parking availability, but there is also plenty of street space if you turn down Monte Vista. Thank you Coronado for continuing to nourish Phoenix.

QqIy-50df3igJWfR-HvMuQ.text: I'm a huge fan of Dark Hall, unfortunately I moved and now is completely out of my way for my morning coffee. Today I went to The Coronado hoping there will be Oatly as one of my milk option and there wasn't. So of course I was disappointed so I order soy milk instead... and is great! The Barista did such a great job steaming the milk! The Coronado and Dark hall have hands down the best vegan espresso drinks.

YiyvSuAWsrMW9wA9Krc9vg.text: Every time we fly into Phoenix, we are amazed at the progressive vegan/vegetarian eateries!  The Coronado is a real veggie gem mixed with a great little bar.  The goat cheese quesadilla was balanced with a jalapeno jam...that is going on our menu back in the ABQ.  The beer list was ample enough for such a small place...the resident, local IPA went perfect with both the quesadilla and tacos!  And the tacos, cauliflower tacos with the fixin's were up there with the best we have ever had...sans the heat.  We will be back...our other favorite veggie place is just down the street!

IUe2GpBgDPrg04ByPjZjLg.text: Huge hit or miss. I've been here on and off and it really depends on who's in the kitchen. I've gotten the same dish, cauliflower tacos religiously. Sometimes they're amazing and look just like the pics. Other times the tortillas are cold, the cauliflower is burnt, no guacamole in it etc. I like them and they make awesome pastries and cocktails, but the inconsistency in the cooking makes me weary at times.

DJmQcZFLrfgpyYCpPHSzcA.text: Very good vegan option with authentic flair. Keep your taste bud expectations high, but your dining experience expectations low. This is basically a hipster trap - you must seat yourself, so as you walk further into the place, it traps you in a tiny dining area with no way out except the way you came, tripping over guests and servers. EPcoUb8_7aCxNBDiGwCkDw.text: Coffee-Only Review: Good cold brew, but astronomical prices. I would love to break my Starbucks habit but it's hard to do when you don't offer bigger iced sizes. Their biggest iced cup is (I think) 16oz which of course is half ice. It's great coffee but way too expensive for not that much volume. I paid $12 for two cold brews plus a small tip. N_1CJOTMucrWdVWIASysTg.text: Of the Vegan/Vegetarian places in the area that I have tried this is my top pick. The cauliflower tacos was fantastic and I absolutely loved the Brussels Caesar salad. I little pricey for lunch but totally worth it.

YO97qj1jMxCoKbn8s9LtKA.text: Absolutely amazing. I got the chili & cornbread to go, and oh my god. The agave butter really brings out the flavor. Adds a perfect sweetness and coolness factor to the chili, which is a bit spicy. Amazing first experience! Beautiful, hip atmosphere; it's a house converted into a restaurant. Love that kind. And service was great. They should keep to-go silverware where it's in reach of the customers because I had to ask for mine, but other than that I have no complaints. Their fresh baked pastries looked to die for... pretty sure they're all vegan... I was so tempted but I had just come from Dark Hall Coffee (the Coronado's sibling) so I told myself "another day Maddie... they'll always be here". Dark Hall will be my next review! All good things at the Coronado. Highly recommend for a vegetarian/vegan, or even for an omnivore because the menu is mostly plant based instead of meat-alternative-based, not so much soy or seitan but instead just vegetables in the entrees.

PtrfnJ2nDIibhGXg-g1mqQ.text: Love that Phoenix is turning houses into funky restaurants. Was seated right away in a cozy, comfortable space. Ordered at the bar and food was out in about 10 mins. I got the cauliflower tacos. The breaded cauliflower is salty and well spiced. Very tasty! The creamy orange sauce on it was lost, not much flavor. I had to search for the guacamole, seems there was a little on the bottom of the tortilla.   The cauliflower was so bomb but I longed for an acidic slaw on it to cut the saltiness of the cauliflower - which was the only other thing I tasted. What can I say? I'm a bold flavors girl.   I'd come back to try other dishes and enjoy the funky house scene. Definitely worth a try.

StidktmGcVBD93ABqIvBSg.text: Cute little spot to grab lunch or a snack. Good service. I've been here twice and agree with others, the parking is horrible but I came this time after the lunch rush so it was fine. PROS: delicious red bean quesadilla and cauliflower tacos.  CONS: Most expensive little glass of lemonande EVER lol.  The lemonade was delish...just not enough when I realized out small the glass was. Make sure you get a little ice.

photos.caption: Photo of The Coronado PHX - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Red bean Quesadilla, cauliflower tacos, and lemonade (delish but overpriced).

hG3rceYNlttQbn3EHGH0Hg.text: I miss Bragg's Diner.  I'm not a vegan, not even a vegetarian.  But Bragg's had some darn good food.  Their Grand Ave restaurant was also set in what was originally the old Bragg's Pie Factory.  And Bragg's Diner lived up to the building's namesake with some delicious sweet treats.  Unfortunately, Bragg's is now long gone.  But the owners of Bragg's quickly reappeared in the building that once housed the old Coronado Cafe.  After a failed attempt to resurrect the Coronado Cafe by the previous owners, Bragg's owner Liam Murtagh and his crew transformed the old cafe into The Coronado.  Just like Bragg's the food here is primarily vegan with a few non-vegan items mixed in.  Let's see what Murtagh has come up with shall we?  The restaurant itself has a very old soul.  The bones of the building on 7th Street and Monte Vista are relatively unchanged after all these years.  There's some noticeable changes in the decor from The Coronado's prior iterations, but overall the setup is the same.  An old house with multiple small rooms on the inside and a roomy patio area on the outside.  Order at the front counter, grab a number, pick a seat.  I picked the tiny corner room in the back where there's seating for just six.  Its a quaint but cozy little corner and there are shelves upon shelves of board games and books back there.  Perfect little area to kill time reading, chatting with friends, or play one of those board games.  For my first go around here, I decided on a burger.  Ah but I did say this place is primarily vegan didn't I?  This burger is made using garbanzo beans and red potatoes.  Topped with spinach, tomato, and agave mustard.  The bun almost has the texture of a hardened buttermilk biscuit, though thankfully not as flaky.  Came with a side of fries.  Also got one of their house made cherry pop tarts because, well it was just staring at me from the pastry case.  Total cost including tax came to about $16.  Admittedly more expensive than a burger meal you'd get elsewhere, but healthier options often are.  The burger was pretty solid.  The difference in texture from a regular burger was noticeable, but for the most part that didn't take away from the flavor profile.  The mustard was definitely the star of this dish.  Not too spicy, but had just enough to give it a little kick.  Very clean flavors and not heavy at all.  The fries were also cooked just right.  Would've liked a little more cherry filling in my pop tart than I got, but it was still a satisfactory dessert.  Overall a good meal and pretty much in line with the type of meals I remember eating at Bragg's.  So now you have three distinct options on 7th Street if you're a vegan.  Green, Nami, and now The Coronado.  The atmosphere here was super chill like that of a coffee house.  The crowd and staff here during my visit were pretty progressive (borderline hippie in some spots), but friendly and relaxed.  Like I said, I'm a carnivore but even I can appreciate when a vegetarian establishment hits on a good concept.  Bragg's had a winning formula for years.  It appears The Coronado has found its mojo too.

k63VES81s-2MsHuo56WTcg.text: I checked out the Coronado on a friend's suggestion to meet for dinner. So glad I did. We went somewhat early about 5ish and there were a few people having drinks/snacks and chatting. Love the outdoor and indoor seating areas. The menu has a lot of options for vegans/vegetarians and I had a hard time deciding what to get. I wish I'd been hungrier to try more foods but that day I had something light the "good morning sandwich" which was great. My friend's ordered Red potato and garbanzo burger, chorizo tacos (I hear are super popular) and the veggie hummus plate. We all loved our food very much. Service was perfect, wouldn't change a thing, will definitely come back!

7vMmDyAsZYrE3KggzD1C0w.text: 3.75....Finally made it to the Coronado. Ordered the Farmyard scramble and Biscuits and Gravy with an egg. Strike one-no decaf coffee. ib952ysakDhiqz5z6lt2Tg.text: This is a pleasant coffee shop and an inconsistent restaurant. The highlight of the menu for me is the cauliflower tacos, but if I'm not willing to indulge in such a high calorie dish I will skip eating here.   Coronado is definitely a place where I'm consistently shocked by how expensive my order is--a drip coffee and a chia pudding for $9?! Vegetarian tacos and a latte--$15?!   Be prepared to really spend here, expect inconsistent food quality, but enjoy the nice space.

eV4XWPRGFRgOGl-eq3rjNA.text: I've been here a few times and try to get something new every time. The fact it's Vegan is great, I am not vegan, so I can say for the "meat lovers" you honestly have no idea. Your food is full of robust flavors and is so scrumptious you forget that you're "missing" and element. The potato tacos?! FANTASTIC. I even got them one time wrapped in lettuce. They were accommodating to my needs and those bad boys were great... I may have ordered two orders of them because they were so delicious!

03CNzzqnDxv94hBpSBvzog.text: Great food! My family is vegan, I am not so I was very iffy about trying Coronado. It was really great! Honestly, it's so tasty and fresh that you wouldn't even know that it was vegan. They have delicious pastries and great lattes!! Highly recommend this restaurant! qMiwNuULmFHiig9oIGUrJQ.text: My wife and I ate at The Coronado on May 27, 2017 while traveling across the country.  We had the cauliflower tacos, avocado toast, biscuits and gravy with tofu scramble on the side.  The overall meal was good.  I always enjoy a restaurant doing something with cauliflower and I recommend the avocado toast.  Even though it sounds plain, the quality of the bread complimented the dish.   Sadly, due to their public anti-law enforcement stances against Phoenix hiring more police officers and their ignorant views of how police are hurting their community; I can not support their establishment.  Phoenix PD is 1,200 officers short for a city of that size and emergency calls can take up to 15 minutes for law enforcement to respond.  The owners Emily and Liam's anti-police stance are so strong they went to a city hearing to oppose any hiring of police officers and make statements of how law enforcement "hurts" the community.  Up until these public statements, my wife and I were planning to go back during our next trip in June.  Now, I am not going to return.  The owners did not know it at the time, but I am a law enforcement officer.  This knowledge of their anti-police views effected my remembrance of my experience there.  So, I am giving two stars for the food and knowing my hard earned money went to help a place that does not welcome law enforcement, which means I was not welcome there.   I hope Yelp keeps my review.  I am an actual customer of this restaurant and their anti-police stances effected my experience of eating there.  Yelp allows other reviews that go beyond the quality of food and this review is no different than other criticisms for cleanliness, decor, and attitude of the servers/owner.  My review is no different.  Since the owners wanted make public their negative views about members of their community  (law enforcement), that should be taken in consideration when making my review of my experience there.  I would have never went to the place if I known I am not welcome. I wished I never gave money to them.

sc0pFQBg6T_fQs-p8E_ZsQ.text: Enjoyed The Coronado with my vegan wife during our trip to Phoenix, even as a non-vegan eater. Food was well seasoned and I was able to add egg to my breakfast sandwich. Seating was limited inside but we found a spot on the patio. We'll be back next time we are in Phoenix!

xrYPlJpPLwRfIeUjvfSSbQ.text: One thing that I'm rather embarrassed to admit upfront is that I've never had a purely vegan meal. Not to belabor the point, but the Coronado has definitely sold me on the proposition of eating a strictly plant based cuisine. Definitely not going to make declarative statements comparing this to other vegan establishments in the valley, but I would recommend this for anybody who wants to either try that branch of cuisine or wants a low key place to grab a tasty meal.   The first thing that sticks out to me is the building itself. It's in a retrofitted older house in the Coronado neighborhood of Phoenix, and that gives it some character. Cramped is a word that you could easily use to describe the interior; I felt like I was about to run into somebody else on a few occasions while inside. I also want to point out the rad pictures in one of the restrooms, just a bunch of kids wearing creepy masks. It doesn't add much overall, but it was enjoyable in a weird way.   As for the food, this is the most positive part about the establishment. My dining companion and I ordered a hummus plate to share, and they had the chorizo tacos with eggs and I had the cauliflower tacos. The hummus plate was delicious; it comes with cucumbers, carrots, fresh jalapenos, and chips. The texture was a little on the chunkier side, but it paired well with the vegetables on the plate. The cauliflower tacos exceeded my expectations by having this tangy, crunchy edge. The guacamole in it also helps tie it all together. It definitely set a high bar for vegan meals in the future. I can't comment on the faux chorizo in those tacos, but my companion had nothing but good things to say about them. Last thing to point out is they have a good drip coffee offering, and it's cool that it has self refills.  So if you want to get some vegan food, this is a place to get it. There may or may not be better vegan options in the area, but to reiterate this was my first experience with vegan cuisine. There are some concerns about the overall tightness of the space here, but it's not enough to ruin the entire experience.

GnIJUnNLssOIoGI-ULTx0g.text: I was so looking forward to eating here after reading the reviews.  But, I realize now that the rating is high because there are few alternative vegan/vegetarian places in Phoenix. The breakfast was fine, just not all what I was hoping for.    Breakfast tofu eggs were spiced but, it was one-note, nothing special.  Breakfast potatoes (fried russet) were served hot but very bland (no veggies, etc).  Avocado on toast came with arugula, sprouts, cashew pesto -- sounds good but did not add up to great.    The herbal tea was amazingly good, as was the service, both at the counter and in the kitchen.  The folks working here are awesome.  The cafe has a choice of seating areas that make it a wonderful choice for small groups, as well as singles eating alone.  The Coronado was fine.  And, for Phoenix it may be outstanding.  But, if you've had good vegan breakfasts elsewhere (Tucson Bentley's; Salt Lake City Vertical Diner, etc), then the Coronado won't meet your expectations.  But, if you are lazy and don't feel like cooking breakfast for yourself, then the Coronado is the place to go.

RhrA8p6qdwJind3He-1cBw.text: Wow. Love this place so much. Have only been twice but i can't wait to come back again super soon. Some of the best vegan food i have had in phoenix so far. The cauliflower tacos taste just like crispy fish tacos and they are so delicious. They have a variety of vegan pastries and a beautiful outdoor seating patio.

xHiQbN7QBpDI-tHoknRUnA.text: I was here on a Sunday. I was very exited to try out this vegan restaurant. My husband and I walked in. There were about 4 empty dirty tables. There was no host and a couple waiters walked past us and did not greet or made eye contact. I assumed I had to order at the cashier. So we walked up to it. The blonde woman who was helping other customers saw us and went back to talking to them. They had already finish ordering but still chatting. I stood there. A waiter thought we were there for a pick up, I clarified and that we were there eat inside and he said "oh". And walked away. Finally it was our turn but the lady at the cashier ignored us. Went back to what she was doing, did not say "Hi" or "Ill be right with you". She just walked away. I stood there for another couple minutes before deciding to leave. I honestly don't know how this place has good reviews with such bad service when all the employees ignore you.

FzCYNrb-gv431AB-4gNkVg.text: This place is just too damn good. My husband and I were in Phoenix for one night and decided to drop in. We got the fried guacamole, red bean quesadillas, and cauliflower tacos- all of which were so delicious we decided to go back for breakfast. Both of us had the breakfast burrito. Once again, delicious. The restaurant has a chill vibe and the service from John and all of the employees was great.

4CFTI2EogMQmM3_tF9Twaw.text: One of my favorite places! The food is yummy, the ambience friendly and inviting! It's a treat every time we get to stop by to eat or just to get some drinks with friends...

-AKpVTsjga3dHsFUmi76hw.text: This place is pretty outstanding. My family and I have been several times in the last couple of months. No meat here but it isn't missed. My wife loves their cauliflower tacos and I get the chili guacamole fries. The chili is amazing and you don't even notice there is no meat. Our 2 year old loves the quesadilla and the staff is very friendly to all of us especially our son. They always have good beer options that change up regularly. Every time we've been we get a cookie or brownie to split between the three of us.  Oh did I forget to mention they make delicious pastries and desserts? They are also worth checking out.

f1NNO_zm-nnFXmfKBInTKQ.text: We wanted to take our friends to a vegan dinner spot for a Saturday night out.  The Coronado came through for us. We had really good vegan and vegetarian (for us) dishes, great service (even though it was counter ordering), and patio seating.  The We also had amazing cookies (rosemary) and bomb Blondie peanut butter brownies.  Oh ya, and a good wine, and a spicy margarita too!  Guacamole chili fries, cauliflower tacos, red bean quesadilla, and mexican Street corn were all on point, very tasty, and presented well!  I would recommend this place even if you aren't vegan or vegetarian!!

IgSdrzHn9s2wwObPvrKPKw.text: Delicious! Who knew that vegetarian food could taste so good!  I had the Red Potato & Garbanzo Burger , this was one of the best burgers I ever had! SOOOO GOOD! Oh and hand cut fries with homemade ketchup really take it to another level. Will definitely go again.

ghaJoLFOQXiqDXrpUd6CIA.text: Really good vegan menu, cozy seating and nice ambience. I got the chorizo tacos, chili guacamole fries, beet burger and coffee. Will be returning often

XkLkuXRXnPruJLwMQGaVLA.text: This is a non meat eaters dream and a charming addition to the historic district. So far for my visits. V0W7yLJOb5jWKRQBU_Q-aw.text: Everything I've had here is delicious, even for a non-vegetarian like myself. My favorite dishes are the chorizo tacos (San Jose sauce!), fried guacamole, and street corn. The coffee is great, also. Do yourself a favor and try The Coronado!

khM0WeLF0LZAzUqd080GSw.text: Good food, better desserts. Definitely will go back again. Staffs also been very helpful
